c and technical personnel are an often quiet presence within the state, but they play an integral role. At the turn of the twentieth century, the provincial government created geology, forestry, fishery, and agronomy services. These new services drew from recently established university technical programs to amass a corps of skilled employees to support their mission: exploiting resources and occupying territory. Stéphane Castonguay traces the history of mining, logging, hunting, fishing, and agriculture in Quebec to reveal how territorial and environmental transformations thus became a tool of government. By helping to define and shape such interventions, scientific activity contributed to state formation and expanded administrative capacity. The lessons that this thoughtful reconceptualization of resource development offers reach well beyond provincial borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdministrative agencieszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aAdministrative agencieszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aAdministrative agencieszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aAdministrative agencieszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aEarth sciencesxGovernment policyzQuébec (Province)y19th century. 0aEarth sciencesxGovernment policyzQuébec (Province)y20th century. 0aEarth sciencesxGovernment policyzQuébec (Province)y19th century. 0aEarth sciencesxGovernment policyzQuébec (Province)y20th century. 0aNatural resourceszQuébec (Province)xManagementxHistoryy19th century. 0aNatural resourceszQuébec (Province)xManagementxHistoryy20th century. 0aNatural resourceszQuébec (Province)xManagementxHistoryy19th century. 0aNatural resourceszQuébec (Province)xManagementxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.